import cv2 as cv
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
im  = cv.imread ('spider.jpeg',cv.IMREAD_COLOR)
im1 = cv.cvtColor(im,cv.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
h_im,s_im,v_im = cv.split(im1)
assert im is not None
x= np.arange(0,256).astype('uint8')
a = 80
#(c)
# a is taken as 80
print('To get a Visually pleasing Output we can use a =',a)
sigma = 70
y = np.minimum(((x)+(a*(np.exp(-(x-128)**2/(2*sigma**2))))/128), 255).astype('uint8')
trasnformation = cv.LUT(s_im,y)
plt.title('Intensity Transformation')
plt.plot(y)
plt.show()
newHSV = cv.merge([h_im,trasnformation,v_im])
result =  cv.cvtColor(newHSV,  cv.COLOR_HSV2BGR)
addition_of_3_planes = cv.add(newHSV, im)
trasnformation = cv.LUT(s_im,y)
fig ,ax = plt.subplots (3,3, figsize= (10,10))
#(a)
ax[0,0].imshow(h_im,cmap = 'gray')
ax[0,0].set_title('Hue')
ax[0,1].imshow(s_im,cmap = 'gray')
ax[0,1].set_title('Saturation')
ax[0,2].imshow(v_im,cmap = 'gray')
ax[0,2].set_title('Value')
ax[1,0].imshow(im, cmap="gray")
# (b)
ax[1,0].set_title("Without Transformation")
ax[1,1].imshow(trasnformation, cmap="gray")
ax[1,1].set_title("With Transformation")
#(d)
ax[1,2].imshow(addition_of_3_planes, cmap="gray")
ax[1,2].set_title("After adding 3-planes")
#(e)
ax[2,0].imshow(im, cmap="gray")
ax[2,0].set_title('Initial image')
ax[2,1].imshow(newHSV, cmap="gray")
ax[2,1].set_title('Vibrance Transformation')
ax[2,2].imshow(addition_of_3_planes, cmap="gray")
ax[2,2].set_title('Vibrance Enhanced Image')
plt.show()

#3
import cv2 as cv
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

gamma_range = np.arange(1.8,2.3,0.1)
img = cv.imread("highlights_and_shadows.jpeg")
assert img is not None
lab_img = cv.cvtColor(img,cv.COLOR_BGR2LAB)
L_channel = lab_img[:,:,0].astype(np.float32)/255
original_l = np.mean(L_channel)
min_mse = np.inf
optimal_gamma = None

for gamma in gamma_range:
    gamma_corrected_L = np.power(L_channel, 1/gamma)
    mse = np.mean((original_l - gamma_corrected_L)**2)
    if mse < min_mse:
        min_mse = mse
        optimal_gamma = gamma

gamma_corrected_L = np.power(L_channel, 1/optimal_gamma)
lab_img[:,:,0] = np.uint8(np.clip(gamma_corrected_L * 255, 0, 255))
gamma_corrected_img = cv.cvtColor(lab_img, cv.COLOR_LAB2BGR)
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 5))
axs[0].imshow(cv.cvtColor(img, cv.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
axs[0].set_title('Original Image')
axs[1].imshow(cv.cvtColor(gamma_corrected_img, cv.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
axs[1].set_title('Gamma Corrected Image')
plt.show()

print("Optimal gamma value: ", optimal_gamma)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 4))
axs[0].hist(L_channel.flatten(), bins=256, range=(0, 1))
axs[0].set_title('Original Image Histogram')
axs[0].set_xlabel('L Channel Intensity')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Pixel Count')
axs[1].hist(gamma_corrected_L.flatten(), bins=256, range=(0, 1))
axs[1].set_title('Gamma Corrected Image Histogram')
axs[1].set_xlabel('L Channel Intensity')
axs[1].set_ylabel('Pixel Count')
plt.show()

Optimal gamma value:  1.8

#4
import cv2
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def histogram_equalization(image_path):
    img = cv2.imread(image_path, 0)
    hist, bins = np.histogram(img.flatten(), 256, [0, 256])
    cdf = hist.cumsum()
    cdf_normalized = cdf * hist.max() / cdf.max()
    img_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(img)
    hist_eq, bins_eq = np.histogram(img_eq.flatten(), 256, [0, 256])
    cdf_eq = hist_eq.cumsum()
    cdf_eq_normalized = cdf_eq * hist_eq.max() / cdf_eq.max()

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.4, hspace=0.4)
    ax[0, 0].imshow(img, cmap='gray')
    ax[0, 0].set_title('Original Image')
    ax[0, 1].plot(cdf_normalized, color='b')
    ax[0, 1].hist(img.flatten(), 256, [0, 256], color='r')
    ax[0, 1].set_xlim([0, 256])
    ax[0, 1].legend(('CDF', 'Histogram'), loc='upper left')
    ax[0, 1].set_title('Histogram of Original Image')
    ax[1, 0].imshow(img_eq, cmap='gray')
    ax[1, 0].set_title('Equalized Image')
    ax[1, 1].plot(cdf_eq_normalized, color='b')
    ax[1, 1].hist(img_eq.flatten(), 256, [0, 256], color='r')
    ax[1, 1].set_xlim([0, 256])
    ax[1, 1].legend(('CDF', 'Histogram'), loc='upper left')
    ax[1, 1].set_title('Histogram of Equalized Image')
    plt.show()

histogram_equalization('washed_out_arial_img.jpeg')

#5
import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
img = cv2.imread('jeniffer.jpeg', cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)
hsv_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
# Spliting into HUE, SATURATION, and VALUE channels
h, s, v = cv2.split(hsv_img)
# Threshold the saturation channel to obtain the foreground mask
mask = cv2.inRange(s, 20, 245)
kernel = cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE, (20, 20))
mask = cv2.morphologyEx(mask, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel)
#getting the foreground using the mask
fg = cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask=mask)
#getting the histogram of the foreground
fg_gray = cv2.cvtColor(fg, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
fg_hist = cv2.calcHist([fg_gray], [0], None, [256], [0, 256])
# Histogram equalization
cumulative_hist = np.cumsum(fg_hist)
num_pixels = cumulative_hist[-1]
equ = (cumulative_hist / num_pixels) * 255
equ = equ.astype('uint8')
fg_equ = cv2.LUT(fg_gray, equ)
# get the background using the inverse of the mask
mask_inv = cv2.bitwise_not(mask)
bg = cv2.bitwise_and(v, v, mask=mask_inv)
# Add the histogram-equalized foreground and the background
img_eq = cv2.add(bg, fg_equ)
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 4, figsize=(16, 8))
axs[0, 0].imshow(h, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 0].set_title('HUE')
axs[0, 1].imshow(s, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 1].set_title('SATURATION')
axs[0, 2].imshow(v, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 2].set_title('VALUE')
axs[0, 3].imshow(mask, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 3].set_title('Foreground Mask')
axs[1, 0].imshow(cv2.cvtColor(fg, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
axs[1, 0].set_title('Foreground')
axs[1, 2].plot(fg_hist)
axs[1, 2].set_title('Foreground Histogram')
axs[1, 3].plot(equ)
axs[1, 3].set_title('Equalization Function')
axs[1, 1].imshow(cv2.cvtColor(img_eq, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
axs[1, 1].set_title('Result')
for ax in axs.flat:
    ax.set_xticks([])
    ax.set_yticks([])
plt.show()
